data:
The project is a partnership between City of Liverpool College and MEP.  The award of this grant would have a major impact on the young people of the Merseyside area and provide a life-changing opportunity. 

The objective of the project is to raise young people’s European career aspirations and increase their employability skills through undertaking a 22-day placement in Grenada.  

The project will engage with 30 learners, with the majority of participants from areas of disadvantage in Liverpool.

Mobility participants will:
•	Undertake linguistic training;
•	Participate in cultural orientation and placement orientation sessions in Grenada ;
•	Undertake a placement within the hospitality and catering sector in Grenada (total of 22 days in placement) ;
•	Undertake a formal review and reflection of the Mobility including linguistic examination and a formal certification ceremony ;
•	Mobility dissemination sessions back in the UK.

By participating in the mobility the participants will:
•	Develop professional  and employability skills;
•	Learn and adapt to an unfamiliar language;
•	Gain new cultural awareness and awareness of other countries’ customs;
•	Be more motivated;
•	Strengthen self-confidence and social skills.

The mobility will greatly enhance the participants’ portfolio/CVs and make the young people better-equipped for the wider European labour force.

•	The mobility will increase learners’ European/international aspiration, developing a global employment market;
•	Both staff and students will bring back new skills that will enhance local, regional and national training and customer experience;
•	Professional staff will have the opportunity to gain and disseminate knowledge to peers on a local, regional, national, European and international level.

Context:  Our society faces challenges of the scope and intensity not seen since the early 1980s. So great is the uncertainty about the political direction of travel in the UK, US and Europe that on a daily basis we continue to see a rolling back of personal freedoms, a threat to democratic values and human rights. We now see the mainstreaming of far-right, anti-immigration anti-Islam homophobic extremists, validating hate speech and encouraging discrimination and hatred against people with ‘protected characteristics’. 

How we respond to the challenges facing young people with 'protected characteristics' ? Our response is to challenge the direction of political travel, through firstly developing and delivering arts engagement mobility experiences that brings young people together from different backgrounds and perspectives to explore create and present collaborative work at cultural events, encouraging people to celebrate the richness and diversity of a multicultural multi-faith contemporary European society. 

What we want to carry out: The main aim of the youth exchange is to develop collaborative performing arts work that promotes, develops and conveys the key message of ‘Our diversity shapes our Creativity’ as well as presenting collaborative work that offers a counter narrative to the UK leaving the European Union. Through collaborative workshops at our theatre space, supported by professional arts trainers and within peer led sessions our project will see creative work carried out that assists in developing key skills and competencies, enabling young people to successfully develop arts products (dance, music and theatre) that offers audiences different views on what is happing in the UK, Europe and the USA in order to expose some of the myths being presented as 'real news' (for example issues around migration and immigration). 

Objectives: In general our mobility project will see the participants gain the knowledge and skills needed to develop and present collaborative performing arts work in public; deliver arts learning workshops as well as engage in exploring ideas for new projects within the Erasmus+ programme priority areas. 

The specific project objectives: 

To provide quality international mobility opportunities for young people from diverse backgrounds;
To enable young people to better understand current political issues that effect them ;
To gain new competences and experiences of the use of the arts as a tool for making positive contributions to society; 
To deepen knowledge, skills and attitude in order to better organize international youth arts engagement projects;
To build participant skills through practical workshops, peer to peer work and partnership building activities;
To provide insight into the impact of the UK leaving the European Union;
To explore arts development activities that act as key tools for combating racism, xenophobia and discrimination; 
To use digital capture and social media platforms to create and disseminate key messages within the project.

The activities we will carry out include:

A1: An advanced planning visit in Liverpool, UK

A2: A Youth Exchange/mobility of youth workers and young people will take place in Liverpool,  July 2018. The basic elements of our exchange activity will include:

Planning and preparation;
Dance and digital workshops/creative sessions;
Peer to peer group learning sessions;
Live performances;
Live presentations;
Sharing work in local community and school contexts
Networking and partnership building;
Developing multimedia and digital products;
Documenting and evaluating through on-line and digital capture;
Developing future collaborative work;

Type of activity: Mobility of youth workers and young people.

Venue: Liverpool United Kingdom.

Planned activity dates: 2nd-15th July 2018.

The working methods envisaged will include:

Discussions;
Peer to peer group learning;
Training sessions led by professional performing and digital artists;
Practical arts skills sessions
Community engagement sessions (schools, refugee, disabled and youth organizations)
Group meetings;
Evaluations;
Networking opportunities;
Inter cultural activities.

Countries involved: The United Kingdom, France, Iceland, Portugal, Italy and the Netherlands.

Tangible impact includes:

1 cultural sector mobility project delivered with 60 young people and 12 workers;
1 high quality digital film created of the project process;
12 short digital films uploaded to social media focusing on each day of the exchange;
5 social media platforms to document the work;
1 collaborative performance delivered twice at the Unity Theatre in Liverpool;
6 peer to peer sessions delivered;
1 community organization receive workshop sessions ;
1 web page per partner specifically created to raise visibility of the project;
New ideas for future Erasmus+ projects and other EU funds realized;
Dissemination of project results to wider sector in all national contexts.
